This solution keeps track of the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates as the cookie moves around the grid.

```java
public class CookieGrid {
    private int minX, minY, maxX, maxY;

    /**
     * Constructor to initialize the CookieGrid with the initial position of the cookie.
     *
     * @param x the initial x-coordinate of the cookie
     * @param y the initial y-coordinate of the cookie
     */
    public CookieGrid(int x, int y) {
        minX = x;
        minY = y;
        maxX = x;
        maxY = y;
    }

    /**
     * Method to move the cookie to a new position on the grid.
     *
     * @param x the new x-coordinate of the cookie
     * @param y the new y-coordinate of the cookie
     */
    public void moveCookie(int x, int y) {
        minX = Math.min(minX, x);
        minY = Math.min(minY, y);
        maxX = Math.max(maxX, x);
        maxY = Math.max(maxY, y);
    }

    /**
     * Method to calculate the area of the minimum rectangle that can cover all visited grid cells.
     *
     * @return the area of the minimum rectangle
     */
    public int getMinAreaRectangle() {
        return (maxX - minX + 1) * (maxY - minY + 1);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Example usage
        CookieGrid cookieGrid = new CookieGrid(1, 1);
        cookieGrid.moveCookie(3, 4);
        cookieGrid.moveCookie(2, 2);
        System.out.println("Minimum area rectangle: " + cookieGrid.getMinAreaRectangle());
    }
}
```

In this code:

*   The `CookieGrid` class represents the grid and keeps track of the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates.
*   The constructor initializes the grid with the initial position of the cookie.
*   The `moveCookie` method updates the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates as the cookie moves around the grid.
*   The `getMinAreaRectangle` method calculates the area of the minimum rectangle that can cover all visited grid cells.
*   In the `main` method, we demonstrate an example usage of the `CookieGrid` class.

The time complexity of this solution is O(1) for each `moveCookie` operation, and the space complexity is O(1) as it uses a constant amount of space to store the minimum and maximum coordinates.<|eot_id|>

