This is incorrect because the area of a square is simply the square of its side length, not the square root of its square.

### Problematic Code

```c
area = sqrt(s);
```

### Corrected Code

To fix this, simply remove the `sqrt` function and assign the value of `s` directly to `area`:

```c
area = s;
```

### Full Corrected Code

Here is the complete corrected code:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
int main()
{
    double area, side;
    printf("Enter the side of the square: ");
    scanf("%lf", &side);
    area = side * side;
    printf("Area of the square is: %.3f", area);
    return 0;
}
```

Note that I also removed the unnecessary `math.h` include, as it's not needed for this code, and the variable `s` is no longer necessary.<|eot_id|>

